Female":"1268–Overleden","1245–Female":"1245–Overleden","1247–1336":"1247–1336","1280–Male":"1280–Overleden","1295–1348":"1295–1348","1301–Male":"1301–Overleden","1239–Male":"1239–Overleden","1243–Female":"1243–Overleden","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1247":"1247","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","before 1295":"vóór 1295","before 1296":"vóór 1296","before 1280":"vóór 1280","England":"England","Rastrick, Yorkshire, England":"Rastrick, Yorkshire, England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1264–before 1296":"1264–before 1296","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1247–1336":"1247–1336","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1295–1348":"1295–1348","1301–Male":"1301–Deceased","1239–Male":"1239–Deceased","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1247":"1247","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","before 1295":"before 1295","before 1296":"before 1296","before 1280":"before 1280","England":"England","Rastrick, Yorkshire, England":"Rastrick, Yorkshire, England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toothill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from various places named with Old English * <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (WR Yorks) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancs), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwicks), and Tothill (Lincs). There are several further minor place-names of this type that may have contributed to the surname. (ii) locative name, occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Totehill</i> in 1251."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuthill","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of <b>Toothill</b>, primarily a Yorkshire habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (Yorkshire) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancashire), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwickshire), and Tothill (Lincolnshire). There are several further minor placenames of this type that may have contributed to the surname. Also occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Totta</i> (genitive <i>Tottan</i>) + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]},{"name":"Tootell","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tothill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Tutill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootal","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tott","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Tot(te)</i> (Old English  <i>Totta</i>,  <i>Tota</i>).  See also  Totty  ,   Tutt  , and compare Sabyna Tottedoghter’, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Kirkby Malham, WR Yorks); Radulphus Totusone, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Frisby on the Wreak, Leics). Some early bearers may belong with (2) or (3).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>tot(te)</i> ‘simpleton, fool’.","3  English: locative name from Middle English  <i>tot(e)</i> ‘lookout hill’ (Old English  <i>tōt(e)</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a lookout hill, or toponymic, for someone from a place so named, such as Toat Farm in Pulborough (Sussex) and Toat Hill in Slinfold (Sussex).  Compare  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tottle","meanings":["1  English:  see  Toothill  .","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name * <i>Totel</i> (Old English  <i>Tottel</i>)."]},{"name":"Tootill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootle","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tuthill  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard De Toothill was born in 1264, in Halifax, Yorkshire, England, his father, Mr. Toothill, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Toothill, was 21. He married Cecilia De Toothill in 1296, in England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. He died before 1296, in Rastrick, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1264–before 1296":"1264–enne 1296","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1247–1336":"1247–1336","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1295–1348":"1295–1348","1301–Male":"1301–Surnud","1239–Male":"1239–Surnud","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1247":"1247","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1243":"1243","before 1295":"enne 1295","before 1296":"enne 1296","before 1280":"enne 1280","England":"England","Rastrick, Yorkshire, England":"Rastrick, Yorkshire, England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1264–before 1296":"1264–ennen vuotta 1296","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","1245–Female":"12